ANTILLEAN AIRLINE
DOUGLAS DC-9-32
When ALM Antillean Airlines acquired
their new DC-9-32 Series aircraft in Jan-
uary 1975 they. also introduced a brand
new livery as illustrated above.
McDonnell Douglas' Art Director,
Creadick visited
Dick
the Dutch
islands in
the Caribbean and was struck by the
combination of old 18th century country
houses, most of them painted orange/
yellow
and
the
expansive blue sky
adorned by stately sailing woolly white
colours. Thus the glorious colours of the
Caribbean were expressed on the outside
as well as in the interior of the new air-
craft; warm yellow, sky blue and cool
breezy white.
The national flag of the Netherlands
Antilles is carried on the aircrafts nose.
The flag - a blue and white cross shows
six white stars and these six stars are also
repeated on the tail of the aircraft - they
symbolise the six islands of the Nether-
lands Antilles. Aruba, Bonaire, Curacao,
Saba,
St. Maarten,
St. Eustatius.
The
DC-9-32 aircraft are named after the first
three islands listed.
ALN
ANTILLEAN AIRLINES
PJ- SNA
The new livery has also been applied to
the ALM Queen Air and to the Twin
Otter PJ-WIA previously
operated by
Windward Island Airways of St. Maarten,
which company is also
owned by the
Government of the Netherland Antilles
of which the ALM President, Mr. C.O.
Yrausquin is also president.
(Photograph and information kindly sup-
plied by A.L.M.)
